# Security and secrets

## Never commit

- `.env`, real `DATABASE_URL`, API keys, tokens, private keys, tunnel credentials
- `SIGNALBRIEF_PLAN.md` (local interview/planning doc — gitignored)
- Personal filesystem paths (`/Users/...`, `C:\Users\...`, home directory shortcuts)
- Real customer PII (names, emails, phones, SSNs) outside intentional demo seed data
- Production hostnames, internal URLs, or Render/Postgres connection strings with passwords

## Safe patterns

- Use `.env.example` with obvious placeholders only (`signalbrief:signalbrief@localhost`)
- Demo accounts use fictional company names and generic roles (`owner@acme-creative.demo`)
- Reference env vars in code: `process.env.DATABASE_URL`, never inline secrets

## Before staging files

- Run `npm run security:scan` (or rely on the pre-commit hook)
- If a file might contain secrets, stop and redact before `git add`
- Do not use `git commit --no-verify` to bypass hooks unless the user explicitly requests it and understands the risk

## If a secret was committed

Tell the user immediately. Do not push. Rotate the credential and rewrite history only if the user asks.
